---

## 📖 Overview

This repository contains the manuscript:

> **Residual Cut Entropy for Tseitin Formulas:  
> An Information-Theoretic Perspective on Exponential OBDD Lower Bounds**

The paper introduces **Residual Cut Entropy (RCE)**, an information-theoretic invariant that quantifies the number of semantically distinct residual Boolean functions induced by a variable partition.

This framework yields:

- A general structural lower bound for OBDD width.
- An exact formula for Tseitin formulas.
- A concise derivation of classical exponential lower bounds.
- A unifying entropy-based interpretation of branching-program complexity.

---

## 🧠 Main Result

For a Tseitin formula on a connected graph \( G=(V,E) \) and edge partition \( E=L \cup R \):

\[
\mathrm{RCE}(L)
=
|V_{\mathrm{cut}}|-c(G[L])+1
\]

where:

- \( V_{\mathrm{cut}} \): vertices incident to both \(L\) and \(R\);
- \( c(G[L]) \): number of connected components of the left subgraph.

Consequently:

\[
\mathrm{OBDD\ Width}(L)
\ge
2^{\mathrm{RCE}(L)}.
\]

---

## 🚀 Key Consequence

For bounded-degree expander graphs:

\[
\mathrm{RCE}(L)=\Omega(n),
\]

which implies:

\[
\mathrm{OBDD\ Size}
=
2^{\Omega(n)}.
\]

This recovers the classic lower bound of Bryant (1986) through a clean information-theoretic argument.

